<paper id="1523766116"><title>Symbolic Bisimulation Minimisation</title><year>1992</year><authors><author org="ENSMP Centre de Mathématiques Appliquées" id="2043329820">Amar Bouali</author><author org="I.N.R.I.A." id="2197689560">Robert de Simone</author></authors><n_citation>64</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>4334996</reference><reference>1492683468</reference><reference>1503973138</reference><reference>1577673148</reference><reference>1979462141</reference><reference>2021473546</reference><reference>2068361557</reference><reference>2080267935</reference><reference>2140431743</reference></references><venue id="1162450063" type="C">Computer Aided Verification</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-56496-9_9</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.44346">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.52502">State diagram</keyword><keyword weight="0.46197">Algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.52923">Binary decision diagram</keyword><keyword weight="0.46582">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.51415">Finite-state machine</keyword><keyword weight="0.51045">Minimisation (psychology)</keyword><keyword weight="0.50912">Timed automaton</keyword><keyword weight="0.62727">Bisimulation</keyword><keyword weight="0.56167">Partition refinement</keyword><keyword weight="0.52296">State space</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We describe a set of algorithmic methods, based on symbolic representation of state space, for minimisation of networks of parallel processes according to bisimulation equivalence. We compute this with the Coarsest Partition Refinement algorithm, using the Binary Decision Diagram structures. The method applies to labelled synchronised vectors of finite automata as the description of systems. We report performances on a couple of examples of a tool being implemented.</abstract></paper>